 We got six rows.

62
00:03:02,100 --> 00:03:05,340
 And then the DELETE statement, DELETE FROM.

63
00:03:05,340 --> 00:03:08,340
 So SQL sometimes has what seems like redundant things,

64
00:03:08,340 --> 00:03:12,140
 and it's a bit more of a wordy language.

65
00:03:12,140 --> 00:03:14,940
 It could say DELETE USERS, but it's like DELETE FROM USERS

66
00:03:14,940 --> 00:03:16,820
 rolls better off the tongue.

67
00:03:16,820 --> 00:03:20,340
 So this is a table, and then WHERE is a part.

68
00:03:20,340 --> 00:03:23,500
 You'll see WHERE clauses on all kinds of SQL statements.

69
00:03:23,500 --> 00:03:25,060
 And if you said DELETE FROM USERS,

70
00:03:25,060 --> 00:03:26,700
 it would actually delete all the records.

71
00:03:26,700 --> 00:03:29,220
 Maybe I'll do that right down here at the bottom.

72
00:03:29,220 --> 00:03:31,740
 But I'm gonna say, I wanna go in and DELETE the record

73
00:03:31,740 --> 00:03:32,740
 where this is true.

74
00:03:32,740 --> 00:03:34,420
 Now there might be more than one record.

75
00:03:34,420 --> 00:03:38,980
 This currently happens to be only one record that has this.

76
00:03:38,980 --> 00:03:40,420
 Better grab that semicolon.

77
00:03:40,420 --> 00:03:42,380
 And so it's gonna change that.

78
00:03:42,380 --> 00:03:44,180
 So I'll DELETE one record.

79
00:03:44,180 --> 00:03:50,180
 So that TED is gone, three, four.

80
00:03:50,180 --> 00:03:52,220
 Oh wait, no, we put TED in twice,

81
00:03:52,220 --> 00:03:54,100
 and it got rid of both of them.

82
