 So it looked through all the records that were in the table

101
00:04:40,300 --> 00:04:42,500
 and it was never true, so nothing got deleted.

102
00:04:42,500 --> 00:04:44,600
 So that's the DELETE statement.

103
00:04:44,600 --> 00:04:46,580
 Now the upper lower case stuff,

104
00:04:46,580 --> 00:04:49,700
 yeah, I'm just kinda, I like the upper case.

105
00:04:49,700 --> 00:04:51,860
 I like to put all my keywords in upper case,

106
00:04:51,860 --> 00:04:54,980
 and then tables, sometimes I don't do upper lower,

107
00:04:54,980 --> 00:04:57,700
 but I tend to use the keywords.

108
00:04:57,700 --> 00:05:00,900
 So UPDATE says to update the table users.

109
00:05:00,900 --> 00:05:03,900
 SET is we're gonna make a change in there.

110
00:05:03,900 --> 00:05:07,900
 Column name equals new value and a WHERE clause.

111
00:05:07,900 --> 00:05:10,200
 And again, if this WHERE clause wasn't there,

112
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:12,020
 it would apply to all of them.

113
00:05:12,020 --> 00:05:17,020
 So this is gonna only set the name to Charles in one place.

114
00:05:17,420 --> 00:05:22,420
 And now, if I do a SELECT, you see that this record here

115
00:05:22,420 --> 00:05:23,660
 got changed there.

116
00:05:23,660 --> 00:05:25,720
 So you can reach in with a WHERE clause

117
00:05:25,720 --> 00:05:29,060
 and update a single comment with an UPDATE statement.

118
00:05:29,060 --> 00:05:33,140
 You can put a WHERE clause on a SELECT,

119
00:05:33,140 --> 00:05:37,160
 so you only see a single row, choop.

120
00:05:37,160 --> 00:05:38,500
 So you only see that row.

121
00:05:38,500 --> 00:05:44,100
 You can add to a SELECT an ORDER BY a column,

122
00:05:44,100 --> 00:05:47,060
 and that column could be in ascending order,

123
00:05:47,060 --> 00:05:49,900
 ascending, doot, doot, doot, doot, doot, going up.

124
00:05:49,900 --> 00:05:51,880
 And then do the same thing,

125
00:05:51,880 --> 00:05:55,100
 SELECT * FROM USERS ORDER BY NAME, descending.

126
00:05:55,100 --> 00:05:59,060
 So that's gonna go descending, doot, doot, doot, doot, doot.

127
00:05:59,060 --> 00:06:02,040
 Sally, Kristen, Colleen, Charles, down they go.

128
00:06:02,040 --> 00:06:02,880
 So that's it.

129
00:06:02,880 --> 00:06:04,700
 Now, we can drop table users,

130
00:06:04,700 --> 00:06:07,020
 and so this is basically the CRUD.

131
00:06:07,020 --> 00:06:11,640
 INSERT, CRUD is CREATE, READ, UPDATE, DELETE.

132
00:06:11,640 --> 00:06:15,660
 Here it would be INSERT, SELECT, UPDATE, DELETE.

133
00:06:15,660 --> 00:06:18,300
 But CRUD is sort of kind of the classic concept.

134
00:06:18,300 --> 00:06:22,460
 So we can drop this table users, but how about I do this?

135
00:06:22,460 --> 00:06:25,940
 Let me show you this, what happens if I say,

136
00:06:25,940 --> 00:06:28,420
 UPDATE USERS, SET NAME = CHARLES.

137
00:06:28,420 --> 00:06:31,980
 Implied in each one of these SQL statements is,

138
00:06:31,980 --> 00:06:33,300
 it applies to all of them.

139
00:06:33,300 --> 00:06:35,540
 So we got all these records,

140
00:06:35,540 --> 00:06:39,860
 UPDATE USERS, SET NAME = CHARLES, without a WHERE clause.

141
00:06:39,860 --> 00:06:42,500
 And then I say, SELECT * FROM USERS.

142
00:06:42,500 --> 00:06:45,220
 Now you think, oh, that, it did exactly what we told us.

143
00:06:45,220 --> 00:06:48,300
 We didn't say WHERE clause, right?

144
00:06:48,300 --> 00:06:51,020
 And that means all the records are affected.

145
00:06:51,020 --> 00:06:55,760
 So this UPDATE USERS sort of implies all of the records.

146
00:06:55,760 --> 00:06:59,560
 Now, if we say DELETE FROM USERS,

147
00:06:59,560 --> 00:07:01,700
 and then don't put a WHERE clause there,

148
00:07:01,700 --> 00:07:03,940
 you're gonna see what happens.

149
00:07:03,940 --> 00:07:06,020
 DELETE FROM USERS, no WHERE clause,

150
00:07:06,020 --> 00:07:08,880
 implied all of the rows.

151
00:07:08,880 --> 00:07:11,820
 And now I do a SELECT, and there is nothing.

152
00:07:12,820 --> 00:07:15,780
 So that's why these WHERE clauses are so important

153
00:07:15,780 --> 00:07:18,100
 on updates and deletes,

154
00:07:18,100 --> 00:07:20,740
 just so that we know what rows they're supposed to apply to,

155
00:07:20,740 --> 00:07:23,460
 'cause by default, they apply to all rows.

156
00:07:23,460 --> 00:07:25,180
 That's why you don't see loops in SQL,

157
00:07:25,180 --> 00:07:28,780
 because every statement, like the UPDATE,

158
00:07:28,780 --> 00:07:31,060
 the SELECT, and the DELETE,

159
00:07:31,060 --> 00:07:32,700
 they're kind of loops automatically,

160
00:07:32,700 --> 00:07:34,180
 and you have to sort of shut them down

161
00:07:34,180 --> 00:07:37,580
 with an IF statement, as it were, which is that WHERE clause.

162
00:07:37,580 --> 00:07:39,980
 And the last thing we can get is we can drop,

163
00:07:39,980 --> 00:07:41,020
 we can just get rid of the table,

164
00:07:41,020 --> 00:07:43,060
 so that's another SQL statement.

165
00:07:43,060 --> 00:07:45,780
 If we look at .tables, we see we have one,

166
00:07:45,780 --> 00:07:47,580
 and then we say DROP TABLE USERS,

167
00:07:47,580 --> 00:07:50,580
 put a semicolon there, and then say .tables,

168
00:07:50,580 --> 00:07:53,940
 and there are no tables left.

169
00:07:53,940 --> 00:07:55,160
 And then I say .quit.

170
00:07:55,160 --> 00:08:00,020
 And now I've got this file called zip.sqlite3,

171
00:08:00,020 --> 00:08:02,740
 and I can get rid of it without hurting,

172
00:08:02,740 --> 00:08:04,980
 this is just, this isn't a database

173
00:08:04,980 --> 00:08:06,260
 that's running with a server,

174
00:08:06,260 --> 00:08:08,580
 or anything makes any difference.

175
00:08:08,580 --> 00:08:10,980
 So I hope this is useful to you.

176
00:08:10,980 --> 00:08:14,100
 This is a great way for you to sort of look around.

177
00:08:14,100 --> 00:08:16,040
 We look for tables, we do selects,

178
00:08:16,040 --> 00:08:17,560
 we figure out what's going on.

179
00:08:17,560 --> 00:08:19,020
 We can sometimes debug our code

180
00:08:19,020 --> 00:08:22,860
 by looking at our databases at a very low level.

181
00:08:22,860 --> 00:08:24,500
 So I hope this has been helpful to you.

